      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hark! A good question, but you must be careful not to ask it too loudly, or the goblins in the corner might start singing a little tune about how the numbers dance.\n\nFirst, let us remember that a **Fixed Rate Mortgage** is like a goblin who promises to give you exactly the same amount of gold every single day, no matter how many times you try to steal it. The payment stays exactly the same from month one to month one hundred. It is boring, safe, and very predictable.\n\nNow, an **Adjustable Rate Mortgage (ARM)** is like a goblin who says, \"I will give you a little bit of gold today, but then I will decide how much you get tomorrow, and I might even decide to give you more or less based on how you act!\" The interest rate changes over time, so your monthly payment will wobble like a pendulum.\n\nYou asked specifically about the first five years. If you choose the ARM, here is what the goblins in your pocket might be whispering to you about the payment changes:\n\n*   **The \"Welcome\" Phase:** In the first few months, the goblin might be generous, giving you a lower interest rate",
